ey, Derbyshire, , England - Horsley Castle":"Horsley, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Verdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Renaud, Sylvie.","French: habitational name from (Le) Verdon, the name of several places in various parts of France, for example in Dordogne, Gironde, and Marne. Compare   Ferdon  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Verdun, the name of a fief in Vessey (Manche), France. Compare   Verdun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Verdin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ramon, Angel, Luis, Ruben, Azael, Fernando, Fidel, Francisco, Guillermo, Javier.","English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Verdon  .","Altered form of French   Verdun  ."]},{"name":"Ferdon","meanings":["Altered form, under American Dutch influence in New Netherland, of French   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Wearden","meanings":["English (Lancashire): apparently from a placename with Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ as the second element. However, the Victoria County History for Staffordshire identifies John <i>de Werdon</i>, mentioned in 1280, as having his name from Verdun (Manche, France); see   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Verdun","meanings":["French: habitational name from any of several places in France called Verdun. The placename is probably of Gaulish origin, deriving from <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, fortress’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from Verdú in Catalonia (Spain), which has the same origin as the French name (see 1 above).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Verdon  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is very rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":70,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":79,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":114,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Roland de Verdon was born about 1145, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Roland de Verdun."},"et":{"about 1145–":"umbes 1145–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1140":"1140","England":"England","Horsley, Derbyshire, , England - Horsley Castle":"Horsley, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1145–":"noin 1145–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","about 1145":"noin 1145","1140":"1140","England":"England","Horsley, Derbyshire, , England - Horsley Castle":"Horsley, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1145–":"environ 1145–Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1145–Female":"1145–Décédée","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1165":"1165","about 1145":"environ 1145","1140":"1140","England":"Angleterre","Horsley, Derbyshire, , England - Horsley Castle":"Horsley, Derbyshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Roland de Verdon est née environ 1145, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Roland de Verdun."},"de":{"about 1145–":"um 1145–Verstorben","1140–Male":"1140–Verstorben","1165–120